status_message:
Donald Trump was elected president on Nov. 8, and many of us didn't see it coming. Frankly, it's easier to unfollow someone on Facebook than it is to argue with them.

Well friends, the period of putting our hands over our ears and chanting "LA LA LA I CAN'T HEAR YOU" is over. It's time to confront our national divide head-on. And what better time to do that then at the Thanksgiving dinner table? 

Talk to your family about politics this Thanksgiving...on purpose. Make your cousin twice-removed explain his vote, and be prepared to explain yours. If you didn't vote, talk about it. If your family is pretty much all on the same page politically, seek out an old friend or high school acquaintance. 

This is no excuse for name-calling over turkey and stuffing. If your relatives are making the conversation unbearable, shut it down. But if everyone agrees to keep things civil, you might be surprised what starting a dialogue can do. 

We'll be posting conversation starters, preparedness checklists and playbooks to get you through Thanksgiving in one piece. Check back here for daily tips on how you can make Thanksgiving awkward again.
link_name: Make Thanksgiving Awkward Again
